MAC is b6:15:53:7f:29:18 (per interface info), which does not match the host’s permanent neighbor entry.\n\n3) DHCP and local link status for host_2_1_1_1 are normal:\n   - Interface eth0 up, link detected at 10Gb/s.\n   - IP obtained via DHCP: 10.2.1.10/24 with default route via 10.2.1.1 and nameserver 10.200.0.2.\n   - Access switch and distribution router ports are up with normal counters.\n\nImpact assessment\n- host_2_1_1_1 cannot communicate beyond its local interface. It cannot reach its default gateway, DNS, or server farm. Inbound pings from the distribution router also fail (no replies).\n- Other parts of the network (host_1_1_1_1 and server farm) operate normally; OSPF control plane is converged and stable.\n\nFault localization\n- The failure is isolated to host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10). All upstream devices (access switch, distribution router, core, server_access_router, servers, and OSPF) function correctly.\n\nRoot cause analysis\n- Misconfigured static ARP/neigh entry on host_2_1_1_1 for the default gateway IP 10.2.1.1:\n  - Host has a PERMANENT neighbor entry mapping 10.2.1.1 to 00:11:22:33:44:55.\n  - The actual router MAC on that segment is b6:15:53:7f:29:18 (router_dist_2_1 br0).\n  - Consequence:\n    - Packets from host_2_1_1_1 destined to 10.2.1.1 are sent to a nonexistent MAC and are blackholed on the L2 segment.\n    - Pings initiated by the router to the host do reach the host (router has correct ARP for the host), but the host’s replies to the router IP are sent to the wrong MAC and never reach the router, causing ping timeouts.\n- This explains both directions of the observed connectivity failures and aligns with all measurements.\n\nAdditional observations\n- DNS configuration on both hosts points to 10.200.0.2 and is correct.\n- HTTP from host_1_1_1_1 to the load balancer and web servers shows normal name resolution and acceptable performance; no indication of routing asymmetry or path loss in that path.\n- The design constraint that backend